I've talked about this before as a recovering people pleaser/fawner but doing this when not in immediate danger or harm's way also hurts the person doing the people pleasing by actually taking away agency and making it harder to know oneself/stop abandoning oneself.

when you're people pleasing or fawning in many situations, you're not allowing people to get to know the real you. if you are not in immediate danger and fawning isn't necessary for survival, just saying whatever you think someone wants to hear is still lying/a control tactic.

obviously it's nuanced but as a former people pleaser who became that way because of trauma and did it to survive and as someone who's been vigorously working on undoing most of my fawning and people pleasing habits in therapy for 15 years, we've gotta talk about the flip side.

people pleasing is inherently about control and manipulation in order to attain or maintain some sense of control. that doesn't make it inherently bad. there are reasons people become people pleasers to survive or cope. but people pleasing can and does cause a lot of harm. https://t.co/FidD5gE6Af
